title: MCP Single-File Import

!! Importing a Single-File Wiki

If you have a TiddlyWiki as a single HTML file and want to migrate it into a node.js folder served by the MCP server, the import is driven by two write tools: `import_html_wiki` and `extract_html_wiki`. There is no special command-line flag — the server runs normally and the AI assistant orchestrates the import at runtime.

!! What you need

# A wiki folder with the tw-mcp plugin installed (see [[MCP Installation]])
# Your single-file TiddlyWiki HTML file
# An MCP client (Claude Code, Gemini CLI, etc.) connected to the running server

If you don't have a wiki folder yet:

```
tiddlywiki ./mywiki --init server
```

Then edit `./mywiki/tiddlywiki.info` to include the tw-mcp plugin. The file should look like this:

```json
{
  "plugins": [
    "tiddlywiki/tiddlyweb",
    "tiddlywiki/filesystem",
    "wikilabs/tw-mcp"
  ]
}
```

See [[MCP Installation]] for how to get the plugin and set up `TIDDLYWIKI_PLUGIN_PATH`.

The wiki folder must be ''empty'' — no `.tid` files in `tiddlers/` and no `$:/config/FileSystemPaths` yet. The import refuses to run against a populated folder.

!! Step 1 — Start a normal server

```
tiddlywiki ./mywiki --mcp rw listen port=9090
```

This starts a normal MCP server with HTTP listen mode, against an empty wiki. Browse to `http://localhost:9090` to see the empty wiki, and connect your MCP client.

!! Step 2 — Stage the import

Ask your AI assistant to import the file, e.g. ''"Import the wiki at ~/Downloads/my-wiki.html"''. The assistant calls:

```
import_html_wiki(path="~/Downloads/my-wiki.html")
```

This:

# Reads all tiddlers from the HTML file
# Loads them into memory so your wiki is immediately usable in the browser
# Classifies tiddlers (content, system, library plugins, custom plugins, ignored boot/core)
# Adds standard plugins to `tiddlywiki.info` by name (they don't need to be extracted)
# Analyses tags and title prefixes to propose rules for `$:/config/FileSystemPaths`
# Writes the analysis to `$:/temp/mcp/html-import` and a human-readable summary to `Import — Proposed Folder Structure`
# Sets `Import — Proposed Folder Structure` as the default tiddler so it opens in the browser

At this point your tiddlers are ''in memory only'' — nothing has been written to disk yet. Your original HTML file is untouched.

!! How the folder structure works

When tiddlers are saved as individual `.tid` files, they need to go somewhere on disk. By default everything goes into a single `tiddlers/` folder, which can get messy with hundreds of tiddlers.

TiddlyWiki has a built-in configuration called `$:/config/FileSystemPaths` that controls this. It uses filter expressions to sort tiddlers into subfolders based on their tags, titles, or other properties.

For example, if you have 50 tiddlers tagged "Journal" and 30 tiddlers with titles starting with "Recipes/", the proposed rules might look like:

```
[is[system]removeprefix[$:/]addprefix[_system/]]
[tag[Journal]addprefix[journal/]]
[prefix[Recipes/]]
```

This means:

* System tiddlers (`$:/...`) go into `_system/`
* Tiddlers tagged "Journal" go into `journal/`
* Tiddlers with titles like "Recipes/Pasta" keep their natural folder structure
* Everything else stays in the `tiddlers/` root

Tag names with special characters (spaces, parentheses, dots, etc.) are normalised for folder names: spaces become `-`, runs of other non-alphanumeric characters collapse to a single `_`, and leading/trailing separators are trimmed. For example, the tag `Higher Caloric Value (H.C.V.)` becomes the folder `higher-caloric-value-h_c_v`.

For full details see the [[TiddlyWiki documentation|https://tiddlywiki.com/#Customising%20Tiddler%20File%20Naming]].

!! Step 3 — Review the proposed rules

# Refresh `http://localhost:9090` — the tiddler ''Import — Proposed Folder Structure'' opens automatically with the full list of proposed rules
# Review the rules. If you want to change anything, edit `$:/config/FileSystemPaths` directly in the browser
# Save the wiki tab so the AI sees your edits

You can also tell the AI what you'd prefer in plain language — for example: ''"put everything tagged 'Draft' into a drafts folder"'' or ''"don't create subfolders, keep it flat"''.

!! Step 4 — Commit to disk

Tell the assistant to proceed. It calls:

```
extract_html_wiki()
```

The extract tool reads the current `$:/config/FileSystemPaths` from the wiki — so any edits you made in the browser are respected — and writes the staged tiddlers to `.tid` files under `tiddlers/`.

!! Step 5 — Restart once

Restart the server so any newly-added library plugins activate from the updated `tiddlywiki.info`:

```
tiddlywiki ./mywiki --mcp rw listen port=9090
```

!! After extraction

Your wiki folder is now a standard TiddlyWiki node.js edition. You can:

* Edit tiddlers in the browser or through the AI
* Use version control (git) to track changes
* Build a single HTML file again at any time by asking the AI to use `build_wiki`

!! What happens to plugins?

Your single-file wiki likely includes plugins (like the CodeMirror editor or a theme). The import handles them automatically:

* ''Standard plugins'' (ones that ship with TiddlyWiki) are added to `tiddlywiki.info` by name — they don't need to be extracted as tiddlers; TW loads them from its plugin path on boot
* ''Custom plugins'' (3rd-party plugins not in your local plugin path) are written to disk as single `.tid` files — one tiddler per plugin, not exploded into separate sub-tiddlers. TW unpacks them automatically on next boot
* ''Core and boot tiddlers'' are skipped entirely — they're part of TiddlyWiki itself
